Why you should NOT visualize this notebook on github.¶

Some charts/diagrams/features are not visible in github.

  • This impacts all:
    • plotly plots
    • folium maps
    • embedded images
    • and all other dynamic content
    • quarto meta-tags that improves visualization

This is standard and well-known behaviour.

  • While some workarounds could be possible, there are no universal fixes that resolve all the issues.
    • Plotly customization requires installing external tools, but doesn't fix the other issues
    • Standard workarounds (nbviewer) do not work because the github repo is private.

:::

::: {.callout-tip collapse=true}

Recommendation? whenever possible, use the pre-rendered .html file¶

You have 2 options depending on how much you trust my code and how little time you want to dedicate to this review :)

  1. ✅ open the prerendered HTML file, which contains all of the data without any of the rendering limitations that github suffers from
    • Best if you just want to review the analysis and conclusions You have two options for optimal viewing experience:
  2. ✅ open the notebook in jupyterlab (instead of github) and re-run all cells
    • Best if you want to verify that the code works and that the data is not fake

Creating Custom Data Pipelines from scratch¶

For this project, I wanted to explore manipulating data using rudimentary (ie. hand-crafted) data pipelines.

I was inspired by this talk at PyData Eindhoven 2019, by Vincent D. Warmerdam and wanted to iterate a bit over it.

I will try to give you a glimpse of how they operate, so you don't have to check the code (found in utils/pipeline_utils.py)

Guiding principles¶

  1. I want the notebook to show WHAT I am doing, and move the boring HOW to a separate module
  2. If the "HOW I am doing something" is very relevant, I might leave it in the notebook to avoid forcing context switching on the reader
  3. The Pipeline should be a stateful object that contains a dataframe and one method to apply transformations to it.
    1. The dataframe is taken in when the pipeline is created
    2. The operations are applied as steps which (might) mutate the dataframe
    3. The additional "property bag" is there so that some operations (that produce additional information) can store it there, for future retrieval
  4. The Pipeline should also have additional methods to provide basic observability (see the current state of the data, which operations have been applied, in which order, how long each took to complete, etc...)
  5. One pipeline can be cloned/forked into two, if needed, to avoid having to do common work multiple times.
    1. Upon cloning, the new pipeline retains all of the context from its parent pipeline (metadata: steps, property bag) and also retains a copy of the dataframe at that point in time.

Here's a small diagram to visualize how they work

%%plantuml

@startuml
|matches pipeline|
start
:match_p = pipes.Pipeline(raw_match_df);
:match_p.step(remove_invalid_matches);
note right: custom cleaning function
:match_p.step(drop_columns, columns=cols);
note right: custom cleaning\n function w/ params
if (player_p = match_p.clone()) then (pipeline continues)
    |matches pipeline|
    :match_p.step(other_cleaning_step);
    :match_p.peek(plot_scatter_summary);
    note right: with `.peek()`, no transformation is applied,\nbut it allows inspecting/rendering the data in some way
    :match_p.step(another_operation);
    :match_p.df();
    note right: extract transformed\ndataframe after\nall processing steps
    end
else (a new pipeline is created)
    |players pipeline|
    :player_p.step(extract_players);
    :player_p.step(summarize_players);
    :player_p.step(create_player_model);
    :...;
    end
endif
@enduml

Now that we know how these pipelines work, we can get started.

Understanding our dataset¶

One important thing to remember is that this data is extracted from the EA Sports' FIFA video game series, which raises questions:

  • How was this data collected?
    • How are players assessed?
    • How is this data decided?
      • Is it measured? Is it derived from facts?
      • Is it decided by someone based on their observations?
      • Would different observers reach the same conclusions/results/attributes?
  • These questions apply to the hardest to measure data (player attributes) but could also be asked about everything. e.g:
    • HOW are betting odds captured?
    • WHEN were they captured? (Some companies change their odds as the match progresses...)
    • etc...

Without a clear understanding of this, it will be hard to predict if our model could be improved:

  • Someone's perception of a player's "attack strength" has little to contribute to the game result
  • Actual facts (e.g. number of measured Kms that a player ran over the course of a match) might be an indicator of their actual potential to contribute to the final result (eg. could be an indicator of their stamina or athletic capabilities)

As the data is presented, we will be cautious and try not to take it too strictly.

We hope this caution will allow us to help us detect observer bias (Observer being: FIFA, the creators of the data behind this dataset)

Removing matches with missing data¶

For this next part we want to understand the meaning of missing match data.

For player data that is missing:

  • is it a bug (a data problem that could be solved by improving the data collection methodology)?
  • or is it intentional (does it model the real world correctly)?

Specifically, we want to understand what happens when a match has missing data for one or more of its players.

  • If there is a data bug (missing data cannot be explained), we will have to drop those.
  • If the missing data represents the world correctly (eg. a player got a red card and got kicked out), we might want to include it into our prediction model so it takes it into account.

We will try to find matches that are missing data for players that is not explainable through player expulsions (after receiving 🟨+🟨 2 yellow cards or 🟥 1 red card).

@run
def country_league():
    alpha = 0.05
    q = """
    SELECT c.name, l.name as league, sum(home_team_goal) + sum(away_team_goal) total_goals
    FROM match m
        LEFT JOIN league l ON m.league_id = l.country_id
        INNER JOIN country c ON c.id = l.country_id
    GROUP BY l.name
    ORDER BY total_goals DESC;
    """
    df: DataFrame = sql.query(q)
    df.columns = ["country", "league", "total_goals"]
    sns.barplot(data=df, y="league", x="total_goals", orient="h", color="lightgrey")
    return df

Understanding home team advantage¶

In [84]:
@run
@cached_chart()
def home_advantage():
    alpha = 0.05
    q = """
    SELECT l.name as league, avg(home_team_goal) as avg_home, avg(away_team_goal) as avg_away
    FROM match m
        LEFT JOIN league l ON m.league_id = l.country_id
    GROUP BY l.name;
    """
    df: DataFrame = sql.query(q)
    stat, pval = stats.ttest_ind(df["avg_home"], df["avg_away"])
    if pval < alpha:
        print("these two samples are statistically significantly different")
        print(f"p-val = {pval:.8f}")

    df = df.melt(
        id_vars="league",
        value_vars=["avg_home", "avg_away"],
        var_name="team",
        value_name="avg_score",
    )
    f, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(6, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(data=df, y="league", x="avg_score", hue="team", ax=ax[0])
    sns.kdeplot(data=df, x="avg_score", hue="team", ax=ax[1], bw_adjust=0.5)
    ax[0].set_xlim(0, 3)
    ax[1].set_xlim(0, 3)
    return f

It seems that, when splitting by country/league, there is a clear difference between home goals and away goals. In later analyses we will see that this difference keeps reappearing in different slicings of the data, allowing us to conclude that "home team advantage" seems to be a real thing.

The difference in scores is so small that it keeps the matches more interesting than if it was much larger.

Predicting outcomes of football matches¶

We want to predict the match outcome (win/no-win), and we will try different approaches:

  • Linear models
    1. Using linear regression, we can try to predict the home_team_goal_advantage (difference in goals between the two teams)
      • We expect that the magnitude of the prediction will be useful to understand the model's "confidence" in the predicted result
    2. Using logistic regression, we can try to predict the home_team_win (the win/no-win for the home team).
  • Non Linear models
    1. Using non-linear models, we can try to generate new non-linear features that might give us better results.
  • Statistical models
    1. Using simple statistical models, we can try to predict likelihood of different results, and from there, derive the predicted win/no-win result

Modelling matches¶

We want to build a model that can predict match results.

This will require considerable data wrangling, as we have to process, join and aggregate data from various places.

The end goal is to have something that looks like this:

  • on each row, 1 match
  • columns for all combinations of:
    • team (home/away)
    • position (goalie, defense, midfielder, forward)
    • attribute (all of them: speed, strength, dive, pass, ...)
  • maybe columns for some derived features:
    • e.g. away_forward_advantage = away_forward_strength - (home_defense_strength + home_goalie_strength)
      • how likely is the away team to overpower the home team's defense?)
  • one target column home_team_goal_advantage to predict the result of the match (winner and by how much)
    • we can then use the magnitude of the prediction as a measure of the model's confidence in the team winning/losing (so that, if it ends up predicting a win by 6 points = very confident of a win)

Grouping players based on their positions¶

We want to model the match using all the information we have right now:

  • the teams
  • the players and their positions
  • the attributes for each of the players

This will, ideally give us an overview of the defenses' strength, or the goalie's rating, etc...

To do this, we need to define some cutoff points, this will help us determine how to classify the players. The objective is to cluster players that play similar roles.

These are the roles we have devised:

  • Goalie (Goalkeeper)
  • Defense
  • Midfielder
  • Forward (Striker)
In [32]:
def get_player_positions_all():
    columns = columns_for(
        ["home_player_X", "home_player_Y", "away_player_X", "away_player_Y"]
    )

    positions = sql.query(
        f"""SELECT {", ".join(columns)}
        FROM match
        WHERE away_player_x1 is not NULL"""
    )
    return positions

Based on this quick check, we can make a judgement call and decide on the following cutout points:

The Y axis is horizontal in this chart, since this is the scale that is used in the original dataset. It's just a namin convention we can ignore (no hassle!)

  • Goalies are always on position Y=1 (interestingly, they are all marked as x=1 and y=1)
  • Defenders are between Y=2 and Y=4
  • Midfielders are between Y=4 and Y=8 (included)
  • Forwards are between Y=9 and Y=12 (included)

The cutoff points can be used to categorize players accordingly

def melt_player_y_pos(df):
    return df.melt(
        id_vars=["match_api_id", "date"],
        value_vars=columns_for(["away_player_y", "home_player_y"]),
        value_name="y_position",
        var_name="player_position",
    )


def cast_and_drop_nas(df: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(pd.to_datetime(df["date"]).dt.date)
    df = df[~df["y_position"].isna()]
    df["y_position"] = df["y_position"].astype("int")
    df["player_position"] = df["player_position"].str.replace("_y", "_")
    return df


def assign_player_position_description(df, cuts=dict[str, float]) -> pd.DataFrame:
    df["position"] = "unknown"
    for name, cut in sorted(cuts.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True):
        df.loc[df["y_position"] <= cut, "position"] = name
    return df


match_positions = (
    match_players.clone()
    .step(melt_player_y_pos)
    .step(cast_and_drop_nas)
    .step(assign_player_position_description, cuts=position_cutpoints)
)

Let's enrich our dataset with Score information. We are going to need:

    • We can call this field "home_team_win"

      • 0 if the home team loses/ties (which should capture ~65% of the data)

Does home team advantage exist?¶

We can try to determine if there is statistically significant evidence of "home team advantage":

We could use a couple of different fields to determine this:

In [41]:
ci = 0.95
In [42]:

stats.norm(goal_adv.mean(), goal_adv.std()).interval(confidence=ci)
Out[42]:
(-3.1097901146067786, 3.877102174347338)
In [43]:
goal_adv = goals_p.df()["home_team_win"]
stats.norm(goal_adv.mean(), goal_adv.std()).interval(confidence=ci)
Out[43]:
(-0.517938026060065, 1.4353713375809087)

On the one hand, we can see that, if discount the ties, there are more home wins than away wins.

On the other hand, if we use a confidence interval of 95%, we cannot reject the null hypothesis that there is no such thing as a home team advantage, whether we use "goal difference", or "home team win vs no win"

The split is guaranteed to be the same for both datasets because we used the same random seed (same Index on both dataframes).

However, the scaling will be different, because we are using different scaling strategies:

  • for linear regression, to predict goal difference in home_team_goal_advantage, we used MinMax
  • for logistic regression, to predict win/nowin in home_team_win, we used StandardScaler

Predicting wins using Linear Regression¶

The next step requires us to assess how our data structure works, and if it makes any sense from the domain's point of view.

We can use SelectKBest to see if the data we have put together makes sense.

We expect several things:

  1. Some values will contribute nothing (eg. number of goalkeepers), because they never change (always = 1)
  2. Some values will contribute very little (e.g. number of players in X position), because having 4 players vs 3 players is not as important as who those players are (and their skills)
  3. Some values will contribute a lot (in this regard, I will not make predictions because football is not my strength), but I imagine they would be attributes that my uncle might complain about at the bar... maybe speed, assistance to other players, etc..
  4. Goalkeeper skills:
    1. The goalkeeper attributes of players in the goalkeeper position contribute a lot
    2. The goalkeeper attributes of players NOT in the goalkeeper position contribute almost nothing (eg. no one cares if a midfielder is not great at stopping shots because they never use these skills in matches)
  5. The spread of important features will likely be spread across a variety of attributes (home/away, diverse positions, ...) and will have no discernible pattern (to me, a data scientist with little football watching skills)

let's include them all initially, so we can see if our model correctly identifies contributions that make sense

In [48]:
def calculate_kbest(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, k):
    selector = SelectKBest(score_func=f_regression, k=k)
    selector.fit(X_train, y_train)

    selected_features = selector.get_support(indices=True)
    feature_scores = selector.scores_[selected_features]
    features_series = pd.Series(feature_scores, index=X_train.columns[selected_features])
    features_series_sorted = features_series.sort_values(ascending=False)
    return (
        selector,
        selected_features,
        feature_scores,
        features_series,
        features_series_sorted,
    )


X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = predict_advantage_model.data()

    selected_features,
    feature_scores,
    features_series,
    features_series_sorted,
) = calculate_kbest(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, k=k)

Let's predict match results¶

So, with these results, we're fairly happy that we've been able to do a good job to munge/shape our original data into something that makes sense. Let's call it "good enough" given our limited business insights.

The next step is to use this data to create a brand new model (from scratch) that can predict match results.

As a reminder, let's recall the warning in the kaggle dataset:

The Holy Grail… is obviously to predict the outcome of the game.

The bookies use 3 classes (Home Win, Draw, Away Win). They get it right about 53% of the time. This is also what I've achieved so far using my own SVM. Though it may sound high for such a random sport game, you've got to know that the home team wins about 46% of the time. So the base case (constantly predicting Home Win) has indeed 46% precision.

    Prajit Datta, Dataset author, 2017

  • So... basically:
    • Flip a proverbial coin: 46% success
    • ...
    • Top performing business operating in this space 53%

That's a narrow 7 percentage points of range between the most naive strategy (flip a coin) and strongest ones (the strategies employed by the betting industry with multi-billion $ in profits).

Can you try to guess how our new model will perform?

🍿 Let's get some popcorn and hope for the best

This are not looking great... These are far from the ideal 0.0 (no errors)

When checking with ChatGPT, what could be the cause for this weird behaviour, we get some interesting insights:

Edu: I am trying to use this code to predict match results [...] the issue is that the spread of the predicted results is really poor...

One possible reason for the small spread of predicted values could be that the relationship between the features and the target variable is not linear. Have you tried using a different model, such as a decision tree or a random forest, to see if it improves the spread of predicted values?

This is not ideal, because part of the requirements for this project was to use linear machine learning models. (🤔 Maybe this is the lesson we're here to learn!)

Let's try with a different type of linear model: Logistic Regression

Predicting wins using Logistic Regression¶

Remember that for this predictions we are using a new set of data:

  • we are using predict_win_model instead of predict_advantage_model
  • they were both forked from a common pipeline after initial cleaning
  • they were both scaled (each with its own distinct scaling strategy)
  • predict_win_model is a dataframe created to try to predict the home team win/no win using logistic regression

For this model, we want to select an optimal number of features: too little and our model has terrible performance, too many features and we're deep into overfitting territory.

Let's try to visualize how LogisticRegression performs, depending on the number of features we select:

In [104]:
def prediction_score_for_features(k: int):
    """
    k: number of top features to select using select k best
    """
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = predict_win_model.data()

    (
        selector,
        selected_features,
        feature_scores,
        features_series,
        features_series_sorted,
    ) = calculate_kbest(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, k=k)

    X_train_kbest = X_train.iloc[:, selected_features]
    X_test_kbest = X_test.iloc[:, selected_features]

    random_state = 1
    target_col = "home_team_win"
    model = LogisticRegression(random_state=random_state, max_iter=500)
    model = model.fit(X_train_kbest, y_train)
    predicted = model.predict(X_test_kbest)
    diffs = predicted - y_test
    score = model.score(X_test_kbest, y_test)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, predicted)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, predicted)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, predicted)
    return y_test, predicted, diffs, score, recall, accuracy, precision

Predicting wins using non-linear regression (bonus)¶

Let's use AutoFeat to generate new "maybe-relevant" (and definitely non-linear) features!

Context: I have tried to feed the entire dataframe to AutoFeat to see what happened.

... It did not end well

During the first few attempts it ended up creating 46,000 new features (and running out of memory). Who could have seen it coming?!

To avoid this, we will do 2 things:

  1. Housekeeping Before we start: we want to inspect our memory footprint to see how large are the objects we're handling
  2. New Features When creating new features we will drop the non-contributing features and only use the top 30 or 50 features (according to the SelectKBest)
    • In order to create new features, we will still use the Train portion of our data, to avoid the potential risk of data leakage

def AutoFeatRegressor(*args, **kwargs):
    """
    custom wrapper that ensures we always
    spin up 8 threads for better performance.

    8 is the number of cores in this PC and has been
    empirically tested to be a good balance
    1 thread ~= 80 seconds
    8 threads ~= 20 seconds
    """
    kwargs["n_jobs"] = 8
    disable_advanced_transformations = ()
    return AFR(transformations=disable_advanced_transformations, *args, **kwargs)

def compare_scores(n: int):
    pca_df = match_aggs.df()
    pca_df = pca_df.drop(columns="home_team_win")

    y_pla_df = pca_df[["home_team_goal_advantage"]]
    x_pca_df = pca_df.drop(columns=["home_team_goal_advantage"])

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        x_pca_df, y_pla_df, test_size=0.3, random_state=1
    )

    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train, y_train)
    X_test = scaler.fit_transform(X_test)

    pca = PCA(n_components=n)
    X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_test_pca = pca.transform(X_test)

    kbest = SelectKBest(k=n)
    X_train_kbest = kbest.fit_transform(X_train, y_train)
    X_test_kbest = kbest.transform(X_test)

    lr_pca = LogisticRegression()
    lr_kbest = LogisticRegression()

    lr_pca.fit(X_train_pca, y_train)
    lr_kbest.fit(X_train_kbest, y_train)

    score_pca = lr_pca.score(X_test_pca, y_test)
    score_kb = lr_kbest.score(X_test_kbest, y_test)
    print(n, score_pca, score_kb)
    return score_pca, score_kb

Conclusions¶

This analysis encompasses the ultimate-25k-matches-football dataset https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/prajitdatta/ultimate-25k-matches-football-database-european

  • The data seems roughly clean, despite having a large divide between the matches in terms of data richness. Half the matches are missing detailed data.
  • The analysis shows the importance of trying different approaches to created various models for our data.
    • Some methods (like predicting goal difference) do not perform well, while others (predicting win/no win) show much more promise and outperform the first by an entire order of magnitude.
  • One of the requirements/constraints was to build models only using linear machine learning models (linea/logistic regression).
  • It also includes 2 bonus implementations (using AutoFeat and Principal Component Analysis) to explore options beyond linear models.
    • These models did not noticeably improve the performance of Logistic regression

Executive Summary¶

  • Overall this analysis shines a light into interesting patterns that emerge from the data, which ultimately make us question how this data was collected, and whose guidelines were followed.

    • It seems that the models strongly favour specific metrics (players in the "defense" positions for the home team). When using statistical models that attribute strengths to features, the first 40 features belong to this player group, raising doubts about possible bias in the data.

  • Even with this, the performance of the models created varies from "terrible" to "not too bad", considering the difficulty of predicting matches, and how lucrative this industry is worldwide.

    • If a student who just started to learn machine learning models were able to predict result too well, football betting companies would not be the multi-billion $ industry that it is today.

Lessons Learned¶

These are some interesting things I've learned that I wanted to share

On Computational Performance¶

While some of the tools used in this analysis are absolute time-savers, I did notice growing worried with how long it took to perform some operations (eg. using ydata_profiling to get a quick understanding of the raw data)

Note: For this example I will use ydata_profiling but these also apply to other tools/expensive computations:

I noticed that even though jupyter is configured to use up to 8 cores (threading.active_count()), none of the cores were being fully utilized, so I tried to look for ways to speed up these computations:

  1. I first tried reducing the number of steps used (disabling interactions, then disabling correlations, then using the minimal=True config, then using a small sample of the data: a few 1000s of rows).
    • Did it work?
      • ✅ Some yes. These did work really well, but I wanted to find out how to get the best proverbial bang for the computational buck, and I was also worried that these might omit some important insights.

  2. I then looked for ways to fully utilize that hardware available. This brought new questions:

    • Is there a way to configure jupyter/kernel/IPython/anaconda/python interpreter/runtime engine/virtual machine/threading/OS cpu affinity/...?
    • Is there any way to increase the resources allocated? or to remove limits, so that more cores can be used? or to allow those cores to boost up to 100% utilization?
    • Did it work?
      • ❌ Not really. I couldn't find any way to configure the Python interpreter to use a different number of CPU Cores.
      • The options for multithreading require tools built from the ground up, and while ydata_profiling seems to use multithreading in some of its calculations (e.g when %%time shows that the CPU time is much greater than the Wall time), I don't believe there are low hanging fruit in there.

  3. Is there a way to precompile some code?

    • Numpy is way faster... because it is not python code... so: Is there any way to use a just-in-time compiler to pre-compile part of my code (and, through cascading, the code in the libraries that I will be calling), so that it runs faster?
    • What about Numba and its JIT compiler?
    • Did it work?
      • ❌ No. Numba cannot really optimize code from other imported libraries. It could be used for code that I developed myself, but I cannot simply wrap a call to a library and expect it to compile everything down the call stack.
  4. Is there a way to split up a single call to an external library into various streams (so it can be parallelized)?
    • While it would be possible to split a dataframe into various parts, and create threads for each of those parts, it's also far from ideal.
    • If we split the dataframe by rows, this is just the same as doing a .sample(n) various times.
    • If we split it by columns, this defeats the purpose of the more expensive computations (finding correlations between columns), as some of those correlations will never be calculated. eg. if we have a dataframe with 40 columns and we split it into 4 parts with 10 columns, we're only getting (400=10x10x4) correlations scores instead of the original 1600 = $40 * 40$

While this was a great opportunity to learn more about performance optimization in Python most of the value could be extracted with little cost. In the end, I opted to use:

  • small samples (a few 1000s of rows)
  • include interactions but not correlations.

These are the durations of various runs:

none: few seconds
just interactions: 2m55 (CPU), 0m46sec wall time
just correlations: 4min (CPU), 4m02sec min wall time
both: not even gonna try it. Too long!

I might explore Numba in the future, if I ever need to speed up code that I have written myself and where such an investment results in a noticeable boost that justifies it.

On Perceived Performance¶

While I couldn't really boost the true performance of the computations, I could greatly improve the perceived performance for me and any readers that wanted to explore the notebook.

Using Caching to store/retrieve precomputed data.¶

In order to not have to rerun the notebook from scratch every time, I created a small caching utility that can use serialization to store precomputed data, and to retrieve it at a later date (future runs).

This means that rerunning the entire notebook is a lot faster, since some of the data has already been stored, and reading from disk+rendering is very cheap. The utilities also provide flags to force reruns (for assurance that the stored data is not manipulated and can be recreated at any time, if one is willing to wait for expensive computations to finish).

This library has been created and evolved over the last few projects and it currently supports:

  1. charts: matplotlib, sns
  2. data: pd DataFrames, np arrays
  3. ydata profile reports
  4. any arbitrary objects that support pickling

On using pipelines for data operations¶

Ever since I discovered that talk at PyData Eindhoven 2019, by Vincent D. Warmerdam, I have been wanting to try these.

The PROs¶

They seemed to have lots of benefits:

  • PURPOSE: allowing me to explain transformations as individual steps (thus, requiring a meaningful name)
  • SEPARATION OF CONCERNS: allowing me to split up core components of the cleaning steps:
    • the WHAT: being encoded in the method name + parameters
    • the HOW: (boring details, in most cases): hidden away into a module/function
    • the WHY: explained in the markdown cells
  • METADATA: allowing me to store metadata and returning secondary results
  • PRACTICE: allowing me to practice advanced pythonic data structures/algorithms
  • ...

The CONs¶

But they also had some drawbacks:

  • CONTEXT: It was difficult to sharing context with other people (eg. when showing it to other people/peers in my batch)
    • the opacity of the pipeline, and the lack of familiarity with my specific implementation meant that other people were initially confused as to what this is supposed to be doing, or how it worked.
  • DATA: The initial inertia meant that I was considering using pipelines for ALL non-trivial operations on dataframes.
    • This worked quite well for data cleaning/visualization/EDA/...
    • This worked not so well for creating models

Why roll my own, from scratch?¶

(why reinvent the wheel)

(why reinvent the wheel, without googling what a wheel is?)

Short answer: I really wanted to try it out, as a learning exercise, even if it turned out to be a terrible choice. Most of the issues with pipelines at any scale will likely pop up at a small scale as well, and this provided a good (realistic) environment to explore this.

Since I decided to build my own implementation from scratch (without doing further research into available options), there were several tradeoffs:

  • + No chance of copying/plagiarising existing functionality
  • + No chance of including code without understanding exactly why it exists? Everything I coded actually responds to a specific need I had at some point
  • + It also allowed me to understand the tradeoffs that some of these design decisions carry with them (how should I handle "steps" that don't mutate the data, but that generate/train a model? is the pipeline still the correct structure for this? if not, why not?)
  • - Actively not looking at options available means that, it's likely that I missed some pattern that would have been super useful 🤷‍♂️ oh well...

Fundamentally, it was a very useful learning exercise, and I haven't decided whether I will keep using them in the future.

In general, they seem to help with data transformations, but the rest of the operations (modelling, etc...) doesn't really fit this paradigm.

PS: Now that I have finished my project I did google about Pipelines and noticed that sklearn seems to have the exact same structure builtin using transformers. It seems most of the opeartions I created for my data manipulations could have been done using sklearn's FunctionTransformer :)
